text:
You cant deep dive into something when you have no experience.
When you want to learn to code start small and build gradually from there. Start making a calculator. Then make more complex programs.
Whenever you solve a problem you can most likely solve it or something equivalent in the future.
So the more problems you solve the better you get.
If i would task you with building a simple calculator website with user input to calculate and additionally saving the results and user input in a database.
You wouldnt know where to start.
If you had already created a calculator app. You would now know what to do when you have the input.
Then you can solve the problem how to get the input.
After that you can solve the problem of storing the data.
When i task you the next time with making a login for users.
You would basically know how to get the input and how to store it. You would now â€žonlyâ€œ need to figure out what to do now with user data.

text: Youtube is a very good recource. Learn a simple language such as Python or Javascript to get started. Than master the language, learn all its ins and outs, which in my opinion is best acheived through personal projects, as they will direct your learning. Personally I began with Java than learned C, C++ and am only now learning Python.

text:
As for managing employees, first you need to ask yourself if you are doing what you are supose to, to get people motivated and engaged or are you just a hypocrite.
If you are paying well, have managers who motivate and work enviroment is not hostile and demotivating (literall workplace), then it is cool.
But more often then not, all employers do offer is abuse, not health and safety at worklplace, tragic and chaotic managment and no vision, low pay and no bonuses for hard work and engagment.
